            <pb n="392" facs="#f0001"/>
            <milestone unit="section" rendition="#hr"/>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <div n="1" xml:lang="eng">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Sepulchral Cave in <placeName key="suedamerika">South America</placeName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x2014;In the shady and solitary place, on the<lb break="yes"/>declivity of a
                    high mountain, opens the<lb break="yes"/>cave of <placeName key="ataruipe"
                        >Ataruipe</placeName>. It is less a cave than a<lb break="yes"/>projecting
                    rock, in which the waters have<lb break="yes"/>scoped a great hollow when, in
                    the ancient<lb break="yes"/>revolutions of our planet, they had reach-<lb
                        break="no"/>ed to the height. In this tomb of a whole<lb break="yes"
                    />extinct tribe was soon counted nearly 600<lb break="yes"/>skeletons in good
                    preservation, and arran-<lb break="no"/>ged so regularly that it would have
                        been<lb break="yes"/>difficult to make an error in numbering<lb break="yes"
                    />them. Each skeleton rests upon a kind of<lb break="yes"/>basket formed of the
                    petioles of palms.<lb break="yes"/>These baskets, which the natives call <hi
                        rendition="#i">ma-<lb break="no"/>pires,</hi> have the form of a square
                        bag.&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>Their size is proportional to the age of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>dead; and there are even some for infants<lb break="yes"/>which
                    had died at the moment of birth.&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>We saw them from ten
                    inches and a half<lb break="yes"/>to three feet six inches and a half in
                        length.<lb break="yes"/>All the <choice>
                        <sic>keletons</sic>
                        <corr type="editorial">skeletons</corr>
                    </choice> are bent, and so entire<lb break="yes"/>that no rib or a bone of the
                    fingers and toes<lb break="yes"/>is wanting. The bones have been prepar-<lb
                        break="no"/>ed in three different ways; whitened in<lb break="yes"/>the air
                    and sun, dyed red with aroto, a co-<lb break="no"/>loring matter obtained from
                    the <hi rendition="#i">bixa orel-<lb break="no"/>lanx</hi>; or, like mummies,
                    covered with<lb break="yes"/>odorous resins, and enveloped in leaves of<lb
                        break="yes"/>heliconia and banana. The Indians rela-<lb break="no"/>ted to
                    us that the corpse is first placed in<lb break="yes"/>the humid earth, that the
                    flesh may be con-<lb break="no"/>sumed by degrees. Some months after, it<lb
                        break="yes"/>is taken out and the flesh that remains on<lb break="yes"/>the
                    bones is scraped off with sharp stones.<lb break="yes"/>Near the mapires or
                    baskets there were va-<lb break="no"/>ses of half burnt clay, which appeared
                        to<lb break="yes"/>contain the bones of the same family. The<lb break="yes"
                    />largest of these vases or funeral urns are<lb break="yes"/>three feet two
                    inches high, and four feet<lb break="yes"/>six inches long. The handles are made
                        in<lb break="yes"/>the form of crocodiles or serpents, and the<lb
                        break="yes"/>edge is encircled by meanders, labyrinths,<lb break="yes"/>and
                    greeques, with narrow lines variously<lb break="yes"/>combined.&#x2014;<hi
                        rendition="#i">
                        <persName key="humboldt_av">Humboldt</persName>.</hi></p>
            </div>
